=== The four contexts


The main theme that I wanted to share is that usually I'm speaking in four contexts. You as awareness practitioners, well to me you're very, very special. Particularly if you're aspiring to realize the nature of mind, or you have realized the nature of mind, or you're familiarizing with the nature of mind, or you're effortlessly abiding in and as the nature of mind. 

That's so special to me because it's very, very difficult to come across this approach for one. It's definitely not mainstream, but it is the summit of all vehicles, this very simple awareness. So you do see it everywhere, but this particular approach is not so mainstream. So not only that, if you've realized, if you've even given it a try to even entertain the possibility of a metacognition, of a part of your mind that you haven't explicitly noticed before. To even entertain that is also quite rare in my opinion.

So many beings are content just being in the thoughts. Remember, consciousness can have a thought. Emotion would be considered a thought of consciousness. It's not a linguistic narrating thought---coarse linguistic thought, where the brain organ is heavily involved with that. So certainly when you're thinking a lot, it's totally apparent because the blood flow, the electricity, the tension in the soft tissue of the brain, all of that is self-evident. 

Just like that with the emotional energy, we know when we're in the emotion, there's a contraction, there's blood flow, there's tension, the nervous system is doing things. So the body is a great friend when it comes to natural abiding. Anything that contracts eventually is like you're looking through a microscope and there's nothing there and then all of sudden something appears. You see it right away. Now when you become familiar with awareness, it's like that.

So back to the four contexts. Our little book is based on these four, I call them four phases. And so maybe you haven't recognized the nature of mind. And that's the Dzogchen approach. We say, we're going to point you to this cognition, the basis of the mind. And it's provable, it's nothing mystical, but from the outside, it can certainly appear that way because of the inaccessibility. 

Someone in their thinking mind simply has no idea what you're talking about when it comes to awareness; we've seen that over and over again. So, but there are practitioners that their heart is just onto it. like, yes, I know that this is the truth, maybe I'm not seeing the nature of mind. Because let me be clear about this, if you've seen the nature of mind, there's no doubt. You've had an aha moment. You've had a little click. Not a big fireworks show.

In fact, that's why I don't utilize rituals or ceremonies for pointing out and making a big deal out of it. I believe that years and years of preliminaries could be a hindrance. You could get filled up with religiosity and provisional practices could heavily weigh on you to the point where pointing out loses its simplicity. The recognition happens in a very simple moment. 

So, many of you in these gatherings, for example, to me is an outrageous number of people, have had that click and then you've been able to express yourself from that vantage point. It's just like being on top of a mountain, you're going to speak totally different from the person at the bottom of the mountain describing things. So two different cognitive vantage points there.

And yes, they've proven this meta-awareness. They're not getting into it as heavy as Dzogchen, but they're exploring, and they have gotten into cognitive diffusion in modern neuroscience. They know what it means to be fused into thoughts and emotions, and to be defused from them. If you look at, for example, I always site Herbert Berry statistics, 95% success rate with curing panic altogether through the technique of letting be. So Dzogchen as far as I'm concerned is completely empirically valid. 

But the issue is pointing somebody out, that's still a little mystical, a little mysterious. How do we get there to see this very simple awareness as the basis of mind? They call Gzhi, right? [Dawai spells g-z-h-i] This Gzhi. Gzhi. 

So thankfully in the group, in an intimate setting for sure, we can verify, especially if you talk to people, you talk to the practitioners, to the yogis, you can verify this person has seen the nature of mind. 

Now it's very possible to see it and your thinking mind is just too heavy. It's just too used to being preoccupied. Combined with some kind of stimulants, this could be exasperated, of course. So after pointing out, it really depends on the individual. Like in the Aro Yeshi Jungne text, they have nine different levels of capacities of individuals. The three classes of Dzogchen are ultimately categorized as being, well, which one of these classes is appropriate for which one of these capacities of the individual? Semdé, Longdé, and Menngagdé.

So you have traditionally many levels and ways of pointing out and afterwards, is the practitioner able to sustain that recognition? That's sort of the second. So I was sort of explaining that when I'm speaking here, if you're in the fourth phase, you're completely enlightened, it won't matter what I'm saying. You're going to be cool with it. 

If you're in the third phase where you're effortlessly abiding, and there's self liberation of your confusion of whatever into pure presence, basically, what they call emptiness is starting to come to fruition still. But it hasn't come to full fruition, so you're in the third phase. But you're in pure effortlessness. You have that confidence that Garab Dorje refers to the ding, right? Ding ding ding. So that's the Tibetan word. I'm not just being completely absurd, or maybe I am. So anyway.

So the second phase, I'm going backwards of course, would be, you've seen the view but you're still using little techniques to warm up to it. Or you're just waiting a month, three months to get used to it. It's proving itself to you. Just like I said before, if I turn the one panel on in the heater here, eventually it'll be warm, and that's the proof. Ah, that heater is kicking out some heat. I know because it's warm in the whole shed. Right? 

Well, that's like awareness. When you first see it, you just turned it on, so to speak. And then it gets warmer and warmer and warmer in your life, as it permeates thoughts, emotions, the egoic structure, the self, the division of consciousness, the karmic seeds, the karmic momentum that's resting in the invisible dimensions, what they call the storehouse consciousness, alaya-vijnan, all this is permeated by awareness. At first, all those places are cold. So you have this sort of intermediate period. Is that making sense? All right. 

So you have pre-four phases, then you have recognition, familiarization to the point of pure effortless abiding, and then pure liberation of the mind. Which is essentially, many of you are flickering in and out of that. You're vacillating. And it's just, oh, I'm here, pure presence this is awesome. And then all of a I label it, no, my life is crap. You know, it's that simple. 

The issue is we also carry subtle thoughts like "my life is crap." We think that, you know, somebody could email you even and upset you, say something to you. You stick that down in your repository and it's like an undertow thought---those are the subtle narrations. Still a kind of narration that can go throughout your whole day. You ever have that happen somebody gets to you a little bit and it's just with you all day or some situation, you read a news headline or something? Yeah. It's not coarse---it's not explicit and loud. Just kind of tucked in there. 

And that's why we have the short sessions repeated many times. We get used to that weight coming out, that echo coming off of us. And so let's say I got an email from some crazy person. Today, just as an example. And then we're all... yeah hypothetically speaking, we're all crazy, okay? I mean, no offense. 

So maybe that stuck with me a little bit. So then I come here and I say... oh, before I get here, "I aspire to benefit all beings, and I hope we have a really wonderful session." Well that's my coarse narrative going on. "I hope we have a great session da-da-da," but I'm still, got that tucked in there, right? That, oh, this person, why? You know, something like that, you know? I'm just, so I'm thinking, why wbgy are they saying this? And da-da-da-da. 

But then I also have my sort of deep hurt or whatever from childhood and stuff that doesn't have a linguistic story necessarily anymore. It may have little add-ons that you put in there every now and then you add to... that's called compounding the karma. But it's not going to be explicit like your hurt from childhood, or your worry about your family or something like that, or your regrets or your shame about something, that's going to be tucked in there. 

So if I relax, then I let this whole thought of, "Oh, I hope we have a great session," I let that go. Let the upper sort of clear. And now the email can clear; it can go to the trash. And then now after... this is really actually about five minutes if you're short sessions and you're really getting into awareness practice, and you have a trust there in self liberation, trust---confidence. Then now I'm resting here, the email thing is gone. 

And now other things can begin to come out of my consciousness because I'm not stuffing on top of it. Is that making sense? So by minute 5, minute seven for an average awareness practitioner, you're accessing---those are now being allowed to echo out. And we have this great somatic tuner that basically tells us, are we in tune or are we not? By how the body is feeling. Body is the mind. 

So we may be speaking to somebody and they never even saw the nature of mind. You may have seen it, but it's not completely obvious and apparent on your day and night, the cycle of day and night. Because the cycle... they call it---the cycle of day night---it goes through your awareness. The sun and moon go through your awareness. And you can actually come into this (awareness holds all of it), rather than you being a sort of thing that the sun shines on. Right? 

So any questions so far, or sharing? Yeah, please. 

